# TypeScript Standards

## Strict Mode — Non-Negotiable
- tsconfig must have: `"strict": true`, `"noUncheckedIndexedAccess": true`, `"exactOptionalPropertyTypes": true`
- NEVER use `any`. Use `unknown` and narrow with Zod schemas or type guards.
- NEVER use non-null assertion `!` unless paired with a comment explaining why it's safe.
- All function parameters and return types must be explicitly typed.

## Zod Parsing
- Every external data source (API responses, env vars, user input) MUST be parsed with a Zod schema.
- Pattern: `const parsed = MySchema.safeParse(data); if (!parsed.success) throw new ValidationError(...)`
- Export both the Zod schema AND the inferred type: `export type MyType = z.infer<typeof MySchema>`

## Naming Conventions
- Files: kebab-case (`graph-builder.service.ts`)
- Classes: PascalCase (`AzureDevOpsClient`)
- Interfaces/Types: PascalCase (`AccessGraph`, `GraphNode`)
- Functions/variables: camelCase (`buildAccessGraph`)
- Constants: SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE (`GIT_NAMESPACE_ID`)
- React components: PascalCase files and functions (`GraphCanvas.tsx`)

## Imports
- Use `@/` alias for src-relative imports (configured in tsconfig paths + vite alias)
- Group imports: 1) external libs, 2) internal `@/` imports, 3) relative imports
- Never use `require()` — ESM only

## Error Handling
- All async functions wrapped in try/catch
- Never swallow errors silently — always log or rethrow with context
- Use typed custom error classes: `class AzdoApiError extends Error { statusCode: number }`

## No Magic Numbers
- All Azure DevOps namespace IDs, bitmask values, and API versions live in
  `apps/backend/src/constants/azdo.constants.ts` as named exports
- Reference by name, never inline the raw value

## Comments
- JSDoc on every exported function and type
- Inline comments for non-obvious logic (e.g., bitmask operations, descriptor mapping)